From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Drew Williams <drew.williams@capstanmedical.com>
Date: Tue, 12 May 2026 16:30:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] Pop the recursion blacklist after running an OutPin's
 behaviour

Upstream's recursion-cycle guard in `OutPin<T>::val` is a list of node
UIDs that gets cleared only once per frame, at the end of
`ImNodeFlow::update`. The behaviour code adds the parent's UID before
running, but never removes it. That means once any of a node's output
pins has been pulled this frame, every other output pin on the same
node skips its behaviour and returns a cached (initially indeterminate)
`m_val`.

This silently broke multi-output nodes. In the WPILib filter designer,
a BiquadStage exposes both a Filter wire (the designed cascade) and a
Signal wire (the filtered input). Pull the Signal pin first this frame
and a downstream Bode plot reading the Filter pin sees `m_val_filter`
in its default-initialized state (typically nullptr for pointer types)
and renders empty.

Turn the blacklist into a proper recursion stack: push before the
behaviour, pop after. Real recursion (an OutPin's behaviour pulling its
own node back through an input) is still caught, because the parent's
UID is on the stack during the behaviour call; the second entry sees
it and short-circuits. Once the behaviour finishes the UID pops off,
freeing sibling outputs to run their own behaviours later in the same
frame.

Signed-off-by: Drew Williams <drew.williams@capstanmedical.com>
---
 src/ImNodeFlow.inl | 15 +++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/ImNodeFlow.inl b/src/ImNodeFlow.inl
index fd140f8d80000000000000000000000000000000..fd140f8d80000000000000000000000000000000 100644
--- a/src/ImNodeFlow.inl
+++ b/src/ImNodeFlow.inl
@@ -326,10 +326,21 @@ namespace ImFlow
     template<class T>
     const T &OutPin<T>::val()
     {
-        if (std::find((*m_inf)->get_recursion_blacklist().begin(), (*m_inf)->get_recursion_blacklist().end(), m_parent->getUID()) == (*m_inf)->get_recursion_blacklist().end())
+        // The recursion blacklist is a stack, not a once-per-frame flag:
+        // push the parent's UID before running our behaviour, pop after.
+        // Upstream forgot the pop, which silently broke any node with
+        // more than one output pin — only the first OutPin pulled this
+        // frame ran its behaviour; every subsequent OutPin on the same
+        // node returned its (often indeterminate) cached m_val. With the
+        // pop, the blacklist correctly catches real recursion (an
+        // OutPin's behaviour pulling its own node back through an input)
+        // without poisoning sibling outputs.
+        auto& blacklist = (*m_inf)->get_recursion_blacklist();
+        if (std::find(blacklist.begin(), blacklist.end(), m_parent->getUID()) == blacklist.end())
         {
-            (*m_inf)->get_recursion_blacklist().emplace_back(m_parent->getUID());
+            blacklist.emplace_back(m_parent->getUID());
             m_val = m_behaviour();
+            blacklist.pop_back();
         }

         return m_val;
